Ghana was one of the first countries in sub-Saharan Africa to lower interest rates to counter the virus shock. Ghana’s central bank kept its key interest rate at an eight-year low for a fourth straight meeting as inflation edged closer to target and the economy is rebounding faster than expected. The monetary policy committee kept the rate at 14.5%, Governor Ernest Addison told reporters Monday in the capital, Accra. That matched the forecast of all seven economists in a Bloomberg survey. — With assistance by Simbarashe Gumbo